**VIOLATION OF SINGLE RESPONSIBILITY PRINCIPLE (SRP)**

The class `SystemEventHandler` has more than one reason to change. It handles system events and also sends emails, which are two different responsibilities. This violates the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP). 

To fix this issue, we can create separate classes for handling system events and sending emails. Here is a refactored version of the code:

```java
public class SystemEventHandler {
    private EventRepository eventRepository;
    private EmailService emailService;

    public SystemEventHandler(EventRepository eventRepository, EmailService emailService) {
        this.eventRepository = eventRepository;
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }

    public void handleEvent(String eventType, String payload) {
        if ("USER_CREATED".equals(eventType)) {
            emailService.sendWelcomeEmail(payload);
        } else if ("ORDER_PLACED".equals(eventType)) {
            // Handle order placed event
        }
        eventRepository.saveEvent(eventType, payload);
    }
}
```

In the refactored code, `SystemEventHandler` only handles system events and saves them to a repository. The responsibility of sending emails has been moved to the `EmailService` class:

```java
public class EmailService {
